latestIgtvVideos.title: RAH Tribe
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Kanchana Jaishankar ~ "When I first started modelling, I met some incredibly smart and talented women on set. They were theater practitioners, screenwriters, marine biology students and artists.  And while a picture can tell a thousand words, a carefully curated vision of a designer and his team can often take away from the very real personalities of models, who may actually have a lot say. I am a completely different person from the image of me, which is often portrayed through pictures.
So, to work with the RAH team and to actually be able to express more grounded and real aspects of myself and my personality has been one of the most exciting moments on set that I have ever experienced. It's an idea that I wish would be more prevalent in our industry. With such interesting women and models out there, there remains room for far more interesting conversations as collaborators which are yet to take place. I actually got to bring a little piece of me into these videos and I'm filled with gratitude for the team for letting me do so." Kanchana Jaishankar is a performance artist, actor and a western classical mezzo vocalist trained by Situ Singh Buehler in Opera and Musical Theatre as well as a fashion model. A member of the Lyrics Enemble of Delhi, Kanchana has performed in various settings from Opera to Broadway. She is currently training to study performance and voice further in Europe.

La Vie en Rose ~

Kanchana is covering "Dream a Little Dream of Me", a 1931 song - music by Fabian Andre and Wilbur Schwandt and lyrics by Gus Kahn. No copyright infringement is intended. The song has been used purely as part of a special fashion and arts collaboration project.

latestIgtvVideos.title: RAH Tribe |
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Rosie Cheema ( @rosie4kk ) in a pale gold tulle and silk lehenga from The Sarovar Collection, for her recently held nuptials. The lehenga was wrought with resham, Kashmiri tilla, hand cut sequins and crystals along with dabka and nakshi zardozi, used in a painterly way to render gently floating lotus blossoms and floral buttis derived from pichwai paintings which are further interspersed with baroque motifs and chandeliers. The lehenga was paired with a resham rendered choli and sheer dupattas.

Manvir ( @mcheemaz ) chose a soft pistachio green silk robe for the Anandkaraj ceremony. The jacket was hand-crafted with traditional Varq ka Kaam motifs that were interspersed with zardozi and marodi embroidery rendered using dabka and Kashmiri tilla. The robe was complemented with an embroidered Kamarbandh and Patka. It was layered with a hand printed chanderi silk angrakha and a handloom silk churidaar. The look was completed with a hand printed chanderi silk stole and a pair of hand crafted mojaris.

Photo Courtesy : @alfaazphotography
Video Courtesy : @lucidfilmsinc
Hair and Make Up : @beautybytamanna

Ujjesha Singh (@singhujjesha ) in an ivory tulle and silk lehenga. The skirt featured artworks comprising exotic birds and floral motifs that were derived from archival Persian carpets, interspersed between intricate cutwork panels referenced from 18th-century French lace fragments and handcrafted with zardozi and marodi ka kaam. It was paired with an embroidered choli and a sheer tulle dupatta. The look was completed with an embroidered veil.

Navi (@navii_sarai ) in an ivory- gold silk sherwani. The embroidery motifs were derived from 17th century Mughal artworks and archival Chintz textiles, rendered with resham zardozi, kasab-dori Marodi ka kaam, sequins, and pearls. It was layered over a printed angrakha with sucha gota textures and a cotton churidaar. The look was completed with a vintage Banarasi silk stole that was layered with marodi ka kaam.

latestPosts.caption:
Priya Khunkhun ( @priyasaggu4 ) in a pink tulle and silk lehenga. The skirt was wrought with sucha gota textures, resham zardozi, marodi ka kaam, multi-hued tulle patchwork, sequins and pearls; used to render chevrons and geometric patterns interspersed with floral motifs and resplendent peacocks derived from archival textiles. It was paired with an embroidered blouse and a sheer tulle dupatta.
